<DOC><DOCNO> AP881208-0239 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-88 2338EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Nicaragua-Helicopter     12-08 0247</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Nicaragua-Helicopter,0257</SECOND><HEAD>Honduras Checking if Nicaraguan Pilot was Spy</HEAD><DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Honduras said Thursday it isinvestigating whether a Nicaraguan helicopter pilot was spying whenHonduran authorities intercepted his Soviet-made helicopter gunship.   His mission ``could well have been espionage,'' Foreign MinisterCarlos Lopez said in messages to the United Nations and theOrganization of American States.   Earlier Thursday, Lopez said Honduras has not decided whether togrant political asylum to pilot Edwin Rafael Estrada Leiva, wholanded his helicopter Wednesday at a Honduran air base.   The Nicaraguan government said an army defector flew thehelicopter across the border and described him as a ``CIAterrorist.''   Nicaraguan Foreign Minister Miguel D'Ecoto Brockmann said in aprotest note to Honduras on Wednesday that the helicopter incidentmight be linked to a U.S. plan to invade Nicaragua.   The Honduran armed forces said it intercepted Estrada in Hondurasair space on Wednesday and made him land his Soviet-made MI-25helicopter at an air base near the capital.   Nicaragua immediately demanded the return of the helicopter andpilot. It also accused Honduras of kidnapping the pilot.   The United States funds the war of the Contra rebels againstNicaragua's leftist government, and the Soviet bloc arms Nicaragua.Honduras has allowed the Contras to maintain bases on its territory,and the United States also maintains a military presence there.   Both Honduras and Nicaragua have accused each other of borderincursions, and tension remains high despite a truce in Nicaragua'scivil war.</TEXT></DOC>